#import "template.typ": *

#let metadata = (
  title: "Basic Circuits",
  unit: "Group A (3-Axis) | Phase 2 — Stage C1 | E8, E11",
  author: "C.Moroney",
)

#let lesson = (
title: [Basic Circuits]

,aim: [
Fly the aircraft in the standard circuit pattern, to the stable approach gate, assess for a stable approach and go around. Introduce radio calls.
]

,overview: [
Stage C1 is the first formal circuit lesson. No touch-and-go or full-stop landings are conducted — all approaches are terminated with a go-around. Removing the landing from this stage allows full focus on circuit structure, radio procedures, traffic awareness, and aerodrome management before the workload of the landing is added. The stable approach gate is introduced as a concept and habit from the first circuit. The student will start to take responsibility of the weather briefing in addition to pre-flight documentation and procedures. Because BUMPFISH is introduced for the first time in this briefing, the instructor may complete the BUMPFISH check and make radio calls on behalf of the student in the first one or two circuit sessions. By the subsequent C1 session the student is expected to know BUMPFISH from memory. Radio procedures are practised extensively throughout; formal E13 assessment occurs in Phase 3 Lesson 18.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Describe the NAIPS system: TAF, GAF, and GPWT charts — purpose, format, and how to access
- Describe the circuit pattern and the standard procedures at a non-controlled aerodrome in Class G airspace (AC91-10)
- Describe each circuit leg: upwind, crosswind, downwind, base, final — heights, headings, and spacing references
- Explain right-of-way rules and traffic priority in the circuit
- Recall all recommended radio calls for the full circuit sequence per AC91-10
- Describe the stable approach gate: what it is, where it applies, and what to do if not met
- Explain the BUMPFISH downwind check

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Identify and interpret the NAIPS TAF/GAF/GPWT as appropriate for the aerodrome
- Fly a consistent circuit pattern: correct heights (1000 ft AGL on downwind), spacing, and tracking
- Make all recommended CTAF radio calls with correct phraseology and timing
- Execute a go-around from any point on final: (PA(C)T); full power, attitude, configuration, trim, re-join
- Manage spacing with other circuit traffic
- Apply the BUMPFISH check on every downwind leg
- Assess approach stability at 300 ft AGL and initiate go-around if the gate is not met

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [SA] Maintain a mental map of circuit traffic; using radio assisted see-and-avoid
- [TEM] Identify circuit threats: traffic conflicts, wind gradient, task saturation; pre-brief a forced landing area before the first takeoff of each session
- [HF] Aviate — Navigate — Communicate: aircraft control is always the first priority in the circuit
- [CRM] Radio is a situational awareness tool, not a substitute for SA; fly the aircraft first
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Air Legislation — circuit procedures, right-of-way, non-controlled aerodromes *(Pg 86, 90)*
- Air Legislation — airspace classifications, Class G *(Pg 256)*
- VHF Radio — full circuit call sequence, MAYDAY, PAN *(Pg 55–58, 62–63)*
- Aeroplane Performance — flap effect on descent path *(Pg 127)*
- Human Factors — SA in circuit, stress management, communication errors *(Pg 3, 36–37, 45)*
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 40 minutes \
Equipment required: Local circuit diagram, VTC/airspace diagram, whiteboard, device for NAIPS demonstration \

*Non-Technical Skills* (5 minutes)
- [TEM] Circuit threats: traffic conflicts, wind gradient on final, task saturation; pre-brief EFATO area before the first takeoff of each session
- [SA] Mental map: build and update traffic picture from radio calls and visual scan; know where every aircraft is at all times
- [HF] Aviate — Navigate — Communicate: if the circuit is busy or something goes wrong, fly the aircraft first; radio calls can wait
- [CRM] Radio as an SA tool — other pilots are telling you where they are; use this information

*Circuit Structure — Class G Non-Controlled Aerodrome* (15 minutes)
- Circuit purpose: orderly traffic flow; collision avoidance; predictable positioning for SA
- Legs and heights: upwind (climb to 500 ft, after-takeoff checks, turn crosswind); crosswind (climb to 1000 ft AGL); downwind (parallel to runway, slightly past abeam threshold); base; final
- Standard left-hand circuit unless published otherwise
- Spacing references: runway threshold, aiming point, 45° base turn point
- Right-of-way: aircraft already in circuit have priority; aircraft landing has priority over departing; never cut in front of established traffic
- BUMPFISH checks: completed on downwind — Brakes, Undercarriage, Mixture/Mags, Pump/Prop, Fuel, Instruments, Switches, Hatches and harnesses

*Radio Call Sequence — CTAF* (10 minutes)
- All calls per AC91-10: taxi, backtrack/entering and lining up, base, clear of runway
- Call timing: make each call when at the relevant position; in flight, prioritise aircraft control
- Call structure: callsign, position, altitude, intentions; listen before transmitting
- Active listening: update mental picture from other traffic calls; adjust spacing as required

*Stable Approach Gate* (5 minutes)
- Gate position: 300 ft AGL on final
- Gate criteria — all four must be met:
  - Airspeed: +5/−0 kts of target approach speed
  - Profile: on or slightly above the desired approach path (not below)
  - Alignment: inside runway edge markings — lined up with centreline
  - Configured: correct flap setting
- If any criterion is not met at 300 ft → go-around immediately; no hesitation; this is a rule, not a judgement call
- Go-around procedure: PA(C)T — power, attitude (on horizon), clean up, trim; re-join circuit; a go-around is a normal outcome — not a failure

*NAIPS* (5 minutes)
- NAIPS: TAFs, GAFs, GPWT charts; access via app or web; instructor demonstrates access and TAF/GAF/GPWT format
- Forecast: TAF or GAF/GPWT; used to assess if conditions will remain suitable for the planned flight duration
- BOM radar: supplemental visual tool to assess precipitation; not an official forecast source
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Access NAIPS; obtain TAF/GAF/GPWT for home aerodrome and review with student, noting any hazards
- Review maintenance release; walk student through each section; sign the release; explain what the student should look for in future lessons
- Check NOTAMs; brief any relevant to circuit operations

#text(size:12pt)[*Student*]
- Observe instructor obtaining and interpreting TAF/GAF/GPWT from NAIPS; note wind, conditions, validity period
- Complete IMSAFE self-assessment and operations whiteboard
- Lead pre-flight inspection independently; complete documentation
- Set QNH from aerodrome elevation or ATIS/AWIS
- Deliver pre-takeoff safety brief before taxi independently; include EFATO plan for today's runway
- Make all radio calls from startup onward
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Demonstration*]
- Instructor flies first full circuit pattering every action, check, and radio call throughout
- patter BUMPFISH check on downwind; stable approach gate assessment at 300 ft; go-around initiation if not stable, or at the threshold otherwise

#text(size:12pt)[*Student Practice*]
- All circuits flown by student from the second circuit onward; instructor monitors

_First few circuits:_ Because BUMPFISH has only just been introduced, the instructor may complete the BUMPFISH check and make radio calls on the student's behalf while the student focuses on aircraft control, circuit format, and height. As the student's workload reduces, the instructor progressively hands radio calls and BUMPFISH responsibility back to the student within the same session.

_Subsequent circuits:_
- Upwind: climb to 500 ft; choose reference point; turn onto crosswind; 15° AoB
- Crosswind: climb to 1000 ft AGL
- Downwind: BUMPFISH check; identify spacing reference; slow to approach speed
- Base: identify 45° point; turn base while making radio call; begin descent; flaps 2 before final turn
- Final: assess stable approach gate at 300 ft — all four criteria; go-around if any criterion not met
- Go-around: every approach this stage is a go-around; student executes without prompting after second circuit
- Radio calls: student makes all calls without prompting once workload permits; instructor assists in first circuits only
- Spacing: student identifies and adjusts for circuit traffic; verbalises SA picture
- Minimum 4 circuits
- Note: radio competency is practised here as an ongoing skill; formal E13 assessment occurs in Phase 3 Lesson 18
]

,common_errors:[
- *Forgetting BUMPFISH*: Trigger BUMPFISH at the same point every downwind — after the downwind turn complete and spacing checked; complete before power reduction.
- *Overriding the stable approach gate*: If the gate is not met, go-around — no discussion. The gate is not a suggestion.
- *Losing traffic picture*: Verbalise the traffic picture to the instructor on every downwind — say it aloud to build the habit.
- *Radio at expense of flying*: Set attitude and trim; then transmit. Never sacrifice aircraft control for a radio call.
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Self-Assessment* (5 min): Review each circuit; identify which go-arounds were initiated at gate versus below gate; reflect on radio timing.
- *Instructor Feedback* (10 min):
  - Review each circuit: shape, height, spacing, BUMPFISH completion, gate assessment.
  - Radio calls: timing, structure, active listening quality.
  - SA: "How many aircraft were in the circuit? Where were they?"
  - TEM: were threats identified and verbalised proactively?
- *Scenario Reflection* (5 min): "If the stable approach gate criteria are met at 300 ft but the aircraft balloons badly in the hold-off, what do you do?"
- *Next Steps*: Confirm stable approach gate is understood. Learn BUMPFISH from memory before the next session.
]

,standards_for_progression:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Progressing (P) — may advance to C2A*]
- *Circuit profile*: Consistent height ±150 ft on downwind; circuit shape recognisable with minor corrections
- *Radio calls*: Attempts to make calls or prompts instructor to make the call on their behalf; timing occasionally late but self-corrected
- *BUMPFISH*: Completed (by instructor if needed in first circuits); student knows check by second session with occasional reminder of trigger point
- *Go-around*: Procedure correct with minor prompting; configuration and energy managed
- *Stable approach gate*: Concept understood; gate assessed at 300 ft with prompting; go-around initiated when gate not met
- *Traffic awareness*: Builds traffic picture with prompting; visual acquisition attempted

#text(size:12pt)[*Solo Standard (S) — required before C2A*]
- *Circuit profile*: Consistent height ±100 ft on all legs; shape and spacing correct without instructor direction
- *Radio calls*: All recommended calls made with correct structure and timing without prompting
- *BUMPFISH*: Completed at correct position every circuit without prompting; all items covered
- *Go-around*: Full configuration management without prompting; initiated immediately when gate not met
- *Stable approach gate*: Assessed at 300 ft every approach; go-around initiated proactively without prompting when gate not met
- *Traffic awareness*: Maintains and verbalises traffic picture; visually acquires traffic from radio calls
- *Note*: Formal E13 assessment occurs in Phase 3 Lesson 18. Radio competency here is a prerequisite for safe circuit operations, not a formal graded assessment.

- *Outcome*: Recorded in student training record as P, S, or NC with specific comments.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Ceiling >1500 ft AGL; surface wind \<15 knots; crosswind \<5 knots; visibility >5 km. Stable conditions preferred — student needs clear horizon references throughout.
- *Altitude*: Strict circuit height 1000 ft AGL; monitor height deviations on base-to-final — maximum 30° AoB
- *Emergency Procedures*: EFATO brief before every takeoff; student briefs landing area intention before lining up
- *TEM*:
  - Circuit workload is significantly higher than training area — monitor for task saturation; take over radio and BUMPFISH if student shows overload
  - Monitor all turns for bank angle
  - Monitor spacing actively — student may fixate on one task and lose awareness of closing traffic
  - Monitor for student anxiety; pause, assess and continue or return to training area consolidation if needed
]

,homework:[
- *Learn BUMPFISH from memory before the next session* — Brakes, Undercarriage, Mixture/Mags, Pump/Prop, Fuel, Instruments, Switches, Hatches and harnesses
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - Air Legislation: Pg 86, 90 (circuit procedures, right-of-way, VMC at non-controlled aerodromes)
  - Air Legislation: Pg 256 (airspace classifications, Class G)
  - VHF Radio: Pg 55–58, 62–63 (full circuit call sequence, MAYDAY, PAN)
  - Aeroplane Performance: Pg 127 (flap effect on descent path)
  - Human Factors: Pg 3, 36–37, 45 (SA, stress management, communication errors)
- Access NAIPS; practise obtaining the TAF for Gold Coast or Archerfield and note the format
- Practise all circuit radio calls aloud from memory using the GCSFT CTAF handout provided
- Continue Pre-Solo Air Legislation Exam preparation
- Reflect:
  - "What is your personal trigger point for each radio call in the circuit?"
  - "What are the four stable approach gate criteria? What do you do if one is not met at 300 ft?"
]
)

